.TH QMENU "1" "September 2014"
.SH NAME
qmenu \- creates textual menus.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B qmenu [\fIOPTION\fR] [menu_file]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\" Add any additional description here
.PP
qmenu creates textual menus in an easy and intuitive way.
.TP
\fB\-init\fR
creating configuration file "qmenu.cfg"
.TP
\fB\-model\fR
creating menu file model named "model.mnu"
.TP
\fBmenu_file\fR
file (with .mnu extension) that contains the visual appearance and the definition of the items

.PP
.SH SYNOPSYS
qmenu allows to create menus for interfaces and characters in an easy and intuitive way\. Each menu is defined in a file (with extension \.mnu) that contains the visual appearance and the definition of the items\. The file is divided on three sections:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

1\. Screen Area
2\. Item Area
3\. Option Area
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Each area is delimited by the characters $$ and %%
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

Screen area
$$
Item area
%%
Option area
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SH "Screen area"
This area starts from the beginning of the file to the symbol $$, and contains the "drawing" of the menu in text format\. Each menu option, to be recognized as selectable, must be enclosed between the symbol ^
.
.P
Example:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

^1\. Option 1^
^2\. Option 2^
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
The options can be selected by using the arrow keys or by pressing the first character of the string\. In this area you can also add some variables with the following syntax:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

x[NAME_VARIABILE]
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
The name of the variable is composed by a prefix (x) and the name between square brackets\. These are the available values:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

* c \- Centered
* l \- Left\-justified
* r \- Right\-justified
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Note: If the symbol is put capitalize the value is shown in reverse
.
.P
Variables can take the following value:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

* TIME \- Current time
* MENUNAME \- Name of the menu
* INFOTERM \- Nome of the terminal
* MNUTRACE \- Path menu
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Special variables:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

& \- Cursor position
${PATH} \- Displays the contents of the environment variable PATH
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Example:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

C[TITLE] \- Menu title centered and in reverse
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SH "Item area"
In this section, for each menu item, you define:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
The action to perform
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
An help message
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
An empty row
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
The format to use for each item is composed by 4 lines:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

1\. Menu option
2\. Command to perform
3\. Help message
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP "1." 4
In the first line, insert the first character of the string which contains the menu option
.
.IP "2." 4
In the second line, is possible to specify:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
A shell command
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
A submenu to open ($menuname without extension)
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Reserved command (return to go to the previous menu, end to quit menu)
.
.IP "" 0

.
.IP "3." 4
In the third line you specify the message\. This message will be shown at the variable TITLE present in the "Screen area"
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Example:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

%1
ls \-lisa; pause
This item show shell file list
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SH "Option area"
This section contains a series of generic settings:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

TITOLO \- Menu title
RVS_ROW=0,22 \- Lines displayed in reverse\. In this case the line 0 and line 22
NOKEYDISP \- Disables automatic visualization of function keys labels (ET[1\-10])
ET[1\-10] \- Text shown to function key n if NOKEYDISP commented
FZ[1\-10] \- Command (shell) for the function key n
PW[1\-10] \- Password to set for the function key n
SHELL=sh \- Pressing shift\-f1 starts a shell session
EDITOR=vi \- Pressing shift\-f2 starts vi with the current menu
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
